BMTDL: Bayesian Multitask Deep Learning for Multimorbidity Risk Prediction
This repository contains the official implementation of the Bayesian Multitask Deep Learning (BMTDL) framework proposed in the paper:
Uncertainty-Aware Multimorbidity Risk Prediction via Bayesian Multitask Deep Learning
Ye Chen, Xiaoqun Qin, Shouping Chen
BMC Medical Informatics and Decision Making (Under Review)
📌 Overview
BMTDL is a unified deep learning framework for predicting the risk of multiple chronic diseases simultaneously. It integrates:
• Multimodal data fusion (EHR, clinical text, wearable time-series) via cross-modal attention
• Dynamic gated multitask learning to capture time-varying inter-disease associations
• Bayesian uncertainty propagation using covariance priors and task-correlated Monte Carlo (MC) dropout
• Causal longitudinal modeling (CLSTM-BPR) to discover dynamic causal pathways from physiological time-series
https://graphical_abstract.png
✨ Key Features
• ✅ End-to-end training for joint prediction of multiple chronic conditions
• ✅ Uncertainty quantification with well-calibrated confidence intervals
• ✅ Missing data robustness via modality masking in the fusion module
• ✅ Causal discovery from wearable device data
• ✅ Comprehensive evaluation including ablation studies, sensitivity analysis, and clinical case studies
📊 Results on NHANES (5 Diseases: DM, HTN, CKD, CHD, Stroke)

Model	Average AUC	Δ (vs. Single-task)	Key Feature
BMTDL (Ours)	0.83	+6.8%	Uncertainty-aware + causal
MTDL (w/o Bayesian)	0.81	+4.1%	Multi-task only
GATET	0.80	+3.8%	Graph-based
Random Forest	0.74	–	Single-task
High-uncertainty samples (12.7% of cohort) showed 4.1× higher misclassification and 2.3× higher intervention response odds.
• Simulated clinical deployment suggested 42% potential reduction in misdiagnoses by flagging uncertain predictions.
🛠️ Requirements
The code is implemented in Python 3.8+ with PyTorch. Main dependencies:
torch>=1.9.0
numpy>=1.19.0
pandas>=1.2.0
scikit-learn>=0.24.0
transformers>=4.5.0  # for BioClinicalBERT
rpy2>=3.4.0          # for R integration (optional)
Install all dependencies via:
pip install -r requirements.txt
Quick Start
1. Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/CIAM-Lab/AdaptVisR.git
cd AdaptVisR
2. Data preparation
• Download NHANES data (2011–2018 cycles) from CDC website
• Place raw data in ./data/raw/
• Run preprocessing script:
python preprocess.py --config configs/preprocess.yaml
3. Train the model
python train.py --config configs/bmtdl.yaml
4. Evaluate and generate figures
python evaluate.py --checkpoint checkpoints/best_model.pt
python visualize.py --results results/
